b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\r\n<workbook_page xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\r\n\txmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\r\n\txmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\r\n\txmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\r\n\txmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/" id="p5_accuracy_precision">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>Accuracy and Precision</title>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="accuracy_precision"/>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<p id="aed7fd3b7c804c809870cc2164a224e6">Scientists typically make repeated measurements of\r\n\t\t\ta quantity to ensure the quality of their findings and to know both the <extra>\r\n\t\t\t\t<anchor>precision</anchor>\r\n\t\t\t\t<meaning>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<material>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>how closely a measurement matches the same measurement when repeated</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</material>\r\n\t\t\t\t</meaning>\r\n\t\t\t</extra> and the <extra>\r\n\t\t\t\t<anchor>accuracy</anchor>\r\n\t\t\t\t<meaning>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<material>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>how closely a measurement aligns with a correct value</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</material>\r\n\t\t\t\t</meaning>\r\n\t\t\t</extra> of their results. Measurements are said to be precise if they yield very\r\n\t\t\tsimilar results when repeated in the same manner. A measurement is considered accurate\r\n\t\t\tif it yields a result that is very close to the true or accepted value. Precise values\r\n\t\t\tagree with each other; accurate values agree with a true value. These characterizations\r\n\t\t\tcan be extended to other contexts, such as the results of an archery competition.</p>\r\n\t\t<image id="d783c881e89a4717939441bb2eb5fa27" src="../webcontent/accurate_precise.jpg"\r\n\t\t\talt="Figures A through C each show targets with holes where the arrows hit. The archer in figure A was both accurate and precise as all 3 arrows are clustered in the center of the target. In figure B, the archer is precise but not accurate, as all 3 arrows are clustered together but to the upper right of the center of the target. In Figure C, the archer is neither accurate nor precise as the 3 holes are not close together and are located both to the upper right and right of the target."\r\n\t\t\tstyle="inline" vertical-align="middle" width="600">\r\n\t\t\t<caption>(a) These arrows are close to both the bull\xe2\x80\x99s eye and one another, so they are\r\n\t\t\t\tboth accurate and precise. (b) These arrows are close to one another but not on\r\n\t\t\t\ttarget, so they are precise but not accurate. (c) These arrows are neither on target\r\n\t\t\t\tnor close to one another, so they are neither accurate nor precise.</caption>\r\n\r\n\t\t</image>\r\n\t\t<p id="c7a0f6b64e7d4c7d818c952dab9df686">Suppose a quality control chemist at a\r\n\t\t\tpharmaceutical company is tasked with checking the accuracy and precision of three\r\n\t\t\tdifferent machines that are meant to dispense 10 ounces (296 mL) of cough syrup into\r\n\t\t\tstorage bottles. She proceeds to use each machine to fill five bottles and then\r\n\t\t\tcarefully determines the actual volume dispensed, obtaining the results tabulated in\r\n\t\t\tTable.</p>\r\n\t\t<table id="a38679555cb24411a8d5ecf2687a172b" summary="" rowstyle="plain">\r\n\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="a1cb907d29d34597b3ae6b50644af28e">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Dispenser #1</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="a0a0c5dc2c3447398b78b17368ab5791">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Dispenser #2</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="a9ca5d0b3e16468e9f6d97c2179a2412">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Dispenser #3</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab9edf313c7eb42cdbcb7562e2de674a6">283.3</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="add69b6ffb73848c18e3001564cd1b0b8">298.3</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ae6bbd4e9a66f44cfa2a5fbc3f6cb8451">296.1</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac86a5d0940e94738afe4acf789e423fc">284.1</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac124ec2773074d3d82d0c516281c252e">294.2</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aa0917562144b448fb585751dfba26383">295.9</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="af594a56b92364734b2ecbe45a7da3461">283.9</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac02df1aa6506459d8c4851690d34c457">296.0</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="af5ab95e043f34a8789502ba64de33253">296.1</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aef22a63bb3034cef8406b2d16c2bb01a">284.0</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab3eb067937834a5aaee9915948cf8a37">297.8</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aad9851e345284f2fa937e13fa048a6f5">296.0</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="acb2d83b6606f43b3876fbed7dd38d533">284.1</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ad525203251ea4fbe864c6457170da7c4">293.9</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab911bf839f32499baaf19faf502bbb70">296.1</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t</table>\r\n\t\t<p id="cb1137e4f697481ba2d36682353715d5">Considering these results, she will report that\r\n\t\t\tdispenser #1 is precise (values all close to one another, within a few tenths of a\r\n\t\t\tmilliliter) but not accurate (none of the values are close to the target value of 296\r\n\t\t\tmL, each being more than 10 mL too low). Results for dispenser #2 represent improved\r\n\t\t\taccuracy (each volume is less than 3 mL away from 296 mL) but worse precision (volumes\r\n\t\t\tvary by more than 4 mL). Finally, she can report that dispenser #3 is working well,\r\n\t\t\tdispensing cough syrup both accurately (all volumes within 0.1 mL of the target volume)\r\n\t\t\tand precisely (volumes differing from each other by no more than 0.2 mL).</p>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="accuracy_presision_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t<p id="c1e819b69e6c4b36a919cf9daf9e8a2c">Let&apos;s take another look at the table in the\r\n\t\t\texercise above. The results of Anita&apos;s measurements, which are neither accurate nor\r\n\t\t\tprecise, represent random error. <extra>\r\n\t\t\t\t<anchor>Random error</anchor>\r\n\t\t\t\t<meaning>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<material>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Error produced from a series of measurement where there is no observable\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tpattern in the results.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</material>\r\n\t\t\t\t</meaning>\r\n\t\t\t</extra> occurs when the results of a series of measurements produce no observable\r\n\t\t\tpattern. Notice that in Anita&apos;s measurements some of the values are below the\r\n\t\t\taccepted value and some are above.</p>\r\n\t\t<p id="ac3559b39109424d9a71d6937fc0b33d">If we consider Lynette&apos;s measured values, we\r\n\t\t\tsee that they are precise, but not accurate. This type of data represents systematic\r\n\t\t\terror. <extra>\r\n\t\t\t\t<anchor>Systematic error</anchor>\r\n\t\t\t\t<meaning>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<material>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Error in a series of data in which there is an observable pattern.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</material>\r\n\t\t\t\t</meaning>\r\n\t\t\t</extra> occurs when the results of a series of measurements produces an observable\r\n\t\t\tpattern. Each of Lynette&apos;s measurements is less than the accepted value by\r\n\t\t\tapproximately the same amount.</p>\r\n\t\t<p id="e360f202e86141229f7c66bb856b1165">When systematic error is present, it is often\r\n\t\t\tpossible to pinpoint the source of the error. In Lynette&apos;s measurements, it may be\r\n\t\t\tpossible that the balance she used to measure the mass of the copper is off by\r\n\t\t\tapproximately 1.7 g. This would be something that would be prudent for Lynette to check\r\n\t\t\tto see if she could determine the source of her error. With random error on the other\r\n\t\t\thand, it is difficult if not impossible to determine the source of the error. While\r\n\t\t\tideally data that is collected in an investigation is both accurate and precise, data\r\n\t\t\twhich shows systematic error is preferable to that which shows random error.</p>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="accuracy_presision_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\r\n\t\t<p id="acd1fb23b94c94376b4bc84872f3274d1"> Adapted from <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface" target="self"\r\n\t\t\t\tinternal="false">Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="self" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p id="f79e02c041cd4203a31f05d0d4048798"> Download for free at <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\r\n\t\t\t\ttarget="self" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t</body>\r\n</workbook_page>\r\n'